    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Condition caused by the early stage of growth of any of several types of mold or fungi, appearing as a white to black downy and often smelly film on the surface of organic materials such as cloth, wood, leather, and paper. The two most common species are Aspergillus glaucus and Penicillium glaucum. Mildew is most often found in warm, damp, dark areas and can often look like dirt. It excretes damaging organic acids, such as citric, oxalic, gluconic, etc., that can discolor dyed textiles, paper, paint and leather. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046852/Roberts and Etherington, Bookbinding and Conservation [online] (2003-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Un crecimiento blanquecino que puede ocurrir en plantas y objetos hechos de materiales orgánicos, tales como tela, madera, cuero y papel; causado por microorganismos cuyas esporas se transforman en hongos en una atmósfera húmeda y cálida, alimentandose del material en el que crecen y produciendo ácidos orgánicos dañinos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Een wittige aangroei die op planten of voorwerpen van organische materialen zoals laken, hout, leer en papier kan voorkomen en die wordt veroorzaakt door micro-organismen waarvan de sporen in een vochtige, warme omgeving kunnen uitgroeien tot een schimmel, waarbij ze zich voeden met het materiaal waarop ze groeien en schadelijke organische zuren produceren.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052403/Van Dale Groot Woordenboek (1998)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099102/Van Dale Ne-En (1991)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>在有機物質上，例如布料、木材、皮革，和紙張的表面，由多種霉菌或真菌，於生長早期階段形成的狀態，會出現白色至黑色、氣味難聞的絨毛薄膜。最常見的兩種為蘋果黑麴病菌(Aspergillus glaucus)和青霉菌(Penicillium glaucum)。霉最常見於溫暖、潮濕、陰暗的區域，且經常看似灰塵。其分泌的有害有機酸，如檸檬酸、草酸、葡萄糖酸等，會使染色的紡織品、紙張，塗料和皮革變色。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
